LOCKED RULES:
- No time units (minutes, hours, miles) in narration. Character confusion about time is fine; narration measuring it is not.
- No street/highway/stop signs, no "highway" — use "road." Geography stays unplaceable.
- No specific car tech or era markers (avoid "dial"; "volume knob" flagged as borderline, watch it).
- Casual/flat delivery is the horror mechanism — no dramatic emphasis on wrong details.
- Ground invented "wrong" details in real facts (commodity prices, real folklore, real radio-format conventions).
- Named demons dropped once, never explained — underlying concept: named regional demons are fragments of one nameless, non-singular entity, grounded in real comparative mythology (Julien d'Huy).
- Stephen — always spelled with "ph."
- No hyphens/em-dashes as clause-connectors. Em dash reserved for radio cut-ins and a character cutting off their own speech.
- Avoid stacking three parallel beats/items/clauses (rule-of-three) — vary to two, or vary the shape.
- Avoid repeating a sentence shape twice in close proximity.
- Avoid root-word repeats close together.
- No filler words — "just" banned specifically.
- Don't narrate/tell what should be shown — no pre-explaining supernatural logic before the character has reason to know it.
- Merge related short beats into paragraphs rather than one-line fragments, unless a line earns standing alone.

EDITORIAL AUDITS TO RUN ON ANY DRAFT:
- Repetition audit — same sentence shape twice close together? Kill one, don't reword.
- Root-word audit — same word root repeated nearby?
- Rule-of-three audit — any beat/list/action stacked in exactly three where two hits harder?
- Cliché-swap audit — stock phrase standing in for a specific one?
- Flinch audit — sitting in the scary/ugly moment, or narrating around it?
- Filler audit — no "just," no adjective-stacking, no hyphens-as-connectors.

